{"title_page": "Maurice Beresford", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name= Maurice Warwick Beresford\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|birth_name= \n|birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1920|2|6}}<ref name=Glasscock>Glasscock, ''The Independent'', 2006</ref>\n|birth_place= [[Sutton Coldfield]]<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|residence= \n|spouse= \n|death_date= {{death date and age|df=yes|2005|12|15|1920|2|6}}<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|death_place= [[Leeds]]<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|resting_place= \n|nationality= British\n|known_for= \n|education= [[Bishop Vesey's Grammar School]]<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|alma_mater= [[Jesus College, Cambridge]]<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|occupation= historian, archaeologist\n}}\n\n'''Maurice Warwick Beresford''', MA, FBA, (6 February 1920 \u2013 15 December 2005) was an English economic historian and medieval archaeologist.\n\n==Academic career==\nBorn in [[Sutton Coldfield]], Beresford was educated at [[Bishop Vesey's Grammar School]] and [[Jesus College, Cambridge]] (MA). He was a [[conscientious objector]] in the [[Second World War]], doing [[social work]] in Birmingham and London.\n\nBeresford became a lecturer at the [[University of Leeds]] in 1948 and was appointed Professor of [[Economic History]] at [[University of Leeds|Leeds]] in 1959, a post he was to hold until his retirement in 1985 when he was given the title [[Emeritus]] Professor.<ref>[http://reporter.leeds.ac.uk/538/s7.htm University of Leeds, Reporter 538, Biographical note]</ref>\n\nBeresford was elected Fellow of the [[British Academy]] (FBA) in 1985.<ref>[http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/dec.cfm?letter=B British Academy, List of deceased fellows] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506060305/http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/dec.cfm?letter=B |date=6 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Research interests==\nIn 1945, while working as a warden at an adult education centre, Beresford discovered the remains of the abandoned village of [[Bittesby]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/dec/22/guardianobituaries.obituaries |work=The Guardian | date=22 December 2005 | last=Dyer | first=Christopher | title=Maurice Beresford: A historian on the trail of England's lost villages (Obituary)}}\n</ref> Thus began a lifelong interest in the subject. Together with [[John Hurst (archaeologist)|John Hurst]] he conducted archaeological excavations at the deserted village of [[Wharram Percy]]. This work became an important impetus for [[medieval archaeology]] in Britain and Europe.\n\nAs an undergraduate, he wrote a paper on parkland in [[Sutton Coldfield]], the beginning of his interest in the interaction between the physical landscape and documents such as maps.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/newspaperRetrieve.do?sort=DateAscend&docLevel=FASCIMILE&prodId=TTDA&tabID=T003&bookId=&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchId=R1&currentPosition=2&qrySerId=Locale%28en%2C%2C%29%3AFQE%3D%28ke%2CNone%2C17%29maurice+beresford%3AAnd%3ALQE%3D%28da%2CNone%2C12%29%3E+12%2F13%2F2005%24&retrieveFormat=MULTIPAGE_DOCUMENT&bucketSubId=&inPS=true&userGroupName=lancs&hilite=y&docPage=article&nav=next&docId=IF502595662&searchTypeName=BasicSearchForm&contentSet=LTO|title=Professor Maurice Beresford: Historian whose painstaking work on deserted medieval communities led to his celebrated book ''The Lost Villages of England'' (Obituary)|work=The Times |date=2 Jan 2006|page= 45|url-access=subscription }}</ref> This interest led to his 1957 publication, ''History on the Ground''.\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Minute Book of a Leicestershire Enclosure |year=1947 |publisher=Thornley Offprint |location=Leicester}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Lost Villages of Yorkshire, Parts I to IV |journal=Yorkshire Archaeological Journal |volume=23 |issue= |year=1951 |publisher=[[Yorkshire Archaeological Society]] |location=Leeds |pages=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Lost Villages of Yorkshire, Parts I to IV Offprint from Yorkshire Archaeological Journal |year=1951 |publisher=[[Yorkshire Archaeological Society]] |location=Leeds}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |authorlink= |author2= |title=The Lost Villages of Medieval England |year=1951 |publisher=[[Royal Geographical Society]] |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Leeds Chamber of Commerce. With an Epilogue by S.J. Batchelder |year=1951 |publisher=Leeds Chamber of Commerce |location=Leeds}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |authorlink= |author2= |title=The Lost Villages of England |year=1954 |publisher=[[Lutterworth Press]] |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=Time and Place |year=1961 |publisher=Leeds University Press |location=Leeds}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Common Informer, the Penal Statutes and Economic Regulation |journal=Economic History Review |year=1957 |series=second |volume=10 |issue=2 |publisher=[[Economic History Society]] |location=Glasgow |pages=222\u2013238 |doi=10.2307/2590859}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Common Informer, the Penal Statutes and Economic Regulation (offprint from Economic History Review) |year=1957 |publisher=[[Economic History Society]] |location=Glasgow}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M.W. |title=Lay Subsidies and Poll Taxes |year=1963 |publisher=Phillimore |location=Chichester}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=Leeds and its Region |year=1967 |publisher=Leeds local executive committee of the [[British Association for the Advancement of Science]] |location=Leeds}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=New Towns of the Middle Ages: Town Plantation in England, Wales and Gascony |year=1967 |publisher=[[Lutterworth Press]] |location=London |isbn=0-7188-0601-8}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Beresford |editor1-first=M. W. |editor2-last=Hurst |editor2-first=J. G. |title=Deserted Medieval Villages: Studies |url=https://archive.org/details/desertedmedieval0000bere |url-access=registration |year=1971 |publisher=[[Lutterworth Press]] |location=Woking |isbn=0-7188-1373-1}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=History on the Ground: Six Studies in Maps and Landscapes |url=https://archive.org/details/historyongrounds0000bere |url-access=registration |year=1971 |publisher=[[Methuen Publishing|Methuen & Co]] |location=London |isbn=0-416-15130-2}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Beresford |first1=M. W. |last2=Finberg |first2=H. P. R. |title=English Medieval Boroughs: A Hand-List |year=1973 |publisher=[[David & Charles]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-7153-5997-5}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=Medieval England: An Aerial Survey |series=Cambridge Air Surveys |year=1979 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=Cambridge |isbn=0-521-21961-2}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=West Riding County Council 1889\u20131974 Historical Studies |year=1979 |publisher=The King's England Press |location= |isbn=0-86181-000-7}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=Maurice |title=Walks Round Red Brick |year=1980 |publisher=Leeds University Press |location= |isbn=0-85316-124-0}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=East End, West End: Face of Leeds During Urbanisation, 1684\u20131842 |series=Publications of the Thoresby Society |year=1988 |publisher=Thoresby Society |location=Leeds |isbn=0-900741-23-6}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Beresford |first1=M. W. |last2=Hurst |first2=J. G. |title=Wharram Percy: Deserted Medieval Village |year=1990 |publisher=[[B.T. Batsford]] |location=London |isbn=0-7134-6114-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Beresford |first= Maurice|title= The Lost Villages of England |edition=revised |publisher= Sutton|year= 1998}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=Leeds in the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries (Miscellany) |year=2008 |publisher=Thoresby Society |location=Leeds |isbn=0-900741-66-X}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite journal |last=Cox |first=Harold |year=2007 |title=Maurice Beresford, 1920\u20132005 |journal=Rural History |volume=18 |issue= |pages=135\u2013136 |publisher= |doi=10.1017/s0956793306002056}}\n*{{cite news |last=Dyer |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Dyer |title=Maurice Beresford, A historian on the trail of England's lost villages |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/dec/22/guardianobituaries.obituaries |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=22 December 2005 |accessdate=}}\n*{{cite news |last=Glasscock |first=Robin |title=Professor Maurice Beresford, Economic historian and author of 'The Lost Villages of England' who pioneered 'landscape history' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-maurice-beresford-522938.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=14 January 2006 |accessdate=}}\n*{{cite news |title=Professor Maurice Beresford, Historian whose painstaking work on deserted medieval communities led to his celebrated book the ''Lost Villages of England'' |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article784127.ece |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=2 January 2006 |accessdate=}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK National Archives ID}}\n*{{worldcat id|lccn-n50-7786}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beresford, Maurice}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:British conscientious objectors]]\n[[Category:Economic historians]]\n[[Category:British medievalists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bishop Vesey's Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:20th-century English historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name= Maurice Warwick Beresford\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|birth_name= \n|birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1920|2|6}}<ref name=Glasscock>Glasscock, ''The Independent'', 2006</ref>\n|birth_place= [[Sutton Coldfield]]<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|residence= \n|spouse= \n|death_date= {{death date and age|df=yes|2005|12|15|1920|2|6}}<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|death_place= [[Leeds]]<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|resting_place= \n|nationality= British\n|known_for= \n|education= [[Bishop Vesey's Grammar School]]<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|alma_mater= [[Jesus College, Cambridge]]<ref name=Glasscock/>\n|occupation= historian, archaeologist\n}}\n\n'''Maurice Warwick Beresford''', MA, FBA, (6 February 1920 \u2013 15 December 2005) was an English economic historian and medieval archaeologist.\n\n==Academic career==\nBorn in [[Sutton Coldfield]], Beresford was educated at [[Bishop Vesey's Grammar School]] and [[Jesus College, Cambridge]] (MA). He was a [[conscientious objector]] in the [[Second World War]], doing [[social work]] in Birmingham and London.\n\nBeresford became a lecturer at the [[University of Leeds]] in 1948 and was appointed Professor of [[Economic History]] at [[University of Leeds|Leeds]] in 1959, a post he was to hold until his retirement in 1985 when he was given the title [[Emeritus]] Professor.<ref>[http://reporter.leeds.ac.uk/538/s7.htm University of Leeds, Reporter 538, Biographical note]</ref>\n\nBeresford was elected Fellow of the [[British Academy]] (FBA) in 1985.<ref>[http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/dec.cfm?letter=B British Academy, List of deceased fellows] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506060305/http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/dec.cfm?letter=B |date=6 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Research interests==\nIn 1945, while working as a warden at an adult education centre, Beresford discovered the remains of the abandoned village of [[Bittesby]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/dec/22/guardianobituaries.obituaries |work=The Guardian | date=22 December 2005 | last=Dyer | first=Christopher | title=Maurice Beresford: A historian on the trail of England's lost villages (Obituary)}}\n</ref> Thus began a lifelong interest in the subject. Together with [[John Hurst (archaeologist)|John Hurst]] he conducted archaeological excavations at the deserted village of [[Wharram Percy]]. This work became an important impetus for [[medieval archaeology]] in Britain and Europe.\n\nAs an undergraduate, he wrote a paper on parkland in [[Sutton Coldfield]], the beginning of his interest in the interaction between the physical landscape and documents such as maps.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/newspaperRetrieve.do?sort=DateAscend&docLevel=FASCIMILE&prodId=TTDA&tabID=T003&bookId=&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchId=R1&currentPosition=2&qrySerId=Locale%28en%2C%2C%29%3AFQE%3D%28ke%2CNone%2C17%29maurice+beresford%3AAnd%3ALQE%3D%28da%2CNone%2C12%29%3E+12%2F13%2F2005%24&retrieveFormat=MULTIPAGE_DOCUMENT&bucketSubId=&inPS=true&userGroupName=lancs&hilite=y&docPage=article&nav=next&docId=IF502595662&searchTypeName=BasicSearchForm&contentSet=LTO|title=Professor Maurice Beresford: Historian whose painstaking work on deserted medieval communities led to his celebrated book ''The Lost Villages of England'' (Obituary)|work=The Times |date=2 Jan 2006|page= 45|url-access=subscription }}</ref> This interest led to his 1957 publication, ''History on the Ground''.\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Minute Book of a Leicestershire Enclosure |year=1947 |publisher=Thornley Offprint |location=Leicester}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Lost Villages of Yorkshire, Parts I to IV |journal=Yorkshire Archaeological Journal |volume=23 |issue= |year=1951 |publisher=[[Yorkshire Archaeological Society]] |location=Leeds |pages=}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Lost Villages of Yorkshire, Parts I to IV Offprint from Yorkshire Archaeological Journal |year=1951 |publisher=[[Yorkshire Archaeological Society]] |location=Leeds}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |authorlink= |author2= |title=The Lost Villages of Medieval England |year=1951 |publisher=[[Royal Geographical Society]] |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Leeds Chamber of Commerce. With an Epilogue by S.J. Batchelder |year=1951 |publisher=Leeds Chamber of Commerce |location=Leeds}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |authorlink= |author2= |title=The Lost Villages of England |year=1954 |publisher=[[Lutterworth Press]] |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=Time and Place |year=1961 |publisher=Leeds University Press |location=Leeds}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Common Informer, the Penal Statutes and Economic Regulation |journal=Economic History Review |year=1957 |series=second |volume=10 |issue=2 |publisher=[[Economic History Society]] |location=Glasgow |pages=222\u2013238 |doi=10.2307/2590859}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=The Common Informer, the Penal Statutes and Economic Regulation (offprint from Economic History Review) |year=1957 |publisher=[[Economic History Society]] |location=Glasgow}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M.W. |title=Lay Subsidies and Poll Taxes |year=1963 |publisher=Phillimore |location=Chichester}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=Leeds and its Region |year=1967 |publisher=Leeds local executive committee of the [[British Association for the Advancement of Science]] |location=Leeds}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beresford |first=M. W. |title=New Towns of the Middle Ages: Town Plantation in England, Wales and Gascony |year=1967 |publisher=[[Lutterworth Press]] |location=London |isbn=0-7188-0601-8}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Beresford |editor1-first=M. W. |editor2-last=Hurst |editor2-first=J.G. |title=Deserted Medieval Villages: Studies |url=https://archive.org/details/desertedmedieval0000bere |url-access=registration |year=1971 |publishe